revision.text:
Growing market acceptance of [[Indexing|index based investing]], using traditional [[Mutual fund | mutual funds]] and [[ETFs |exchange traded funds]], has created a proliferation of index providers, attracted by the idea of licensing their indexes to investment companies in exchange for royalty payments.<ref>{{cite book| author=Rick Ferri| author-link=Rick Ferri| title=All About Index Funds: The Easy Way to Get Started| edition=2nd| publisher=Mcgraw-Hill| date=2008| page=88| isbn=0-07-138705-6}}</ref>
For investors, this growth has created an ever expanding choice of [[index fund]]s. However, the different methods that index providers use to measure and segment the stock market means that returns that can vary considerably over short and intermediate term time frames.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.indexuniverse.com/publications/journalofindexes/joi-articles/2622.html| title=Variance Among Indexes| author=Craig Israelsen| publisher=Index Universe| date=2007| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231020509/http://www.indexuniverse.com/publications/journalofindexes/joi-articles/2622.html| archive-date=December 31, 2012}}</ref>
==Benchmark indexes== The benchmark indexes created by the major index providers share a number of characteristics.
===Benchmark index strategy box=== These characteristics place benchmark indexes in the ''Passive'' security selection and ''Capitalization'' security weighting segment of the Index Strategy Box (see Figure 1). The index weighting of securities is based on the [[Market capitalization |market capitalization]] of the companies included in the index.
{| class="wikitable" |+ Figure 1. Index strategy box<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.portfoliosolutions.com/f-18.html| title=Indexing in the 21st Century| publisher=Portfolio Solutions Inc.| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230043641/http://www.portfoliosolutions.com/f-18.html| archive-date=December 30, 2011}}</ref> |[[File:Benchmark Index Strategy Box.png|250 px]] |}
===Benchmark index style box=== In general, the stock market breaks down into three levels of [[Market capitalization | market capitalization]] and three [[Stock basics#Style | styles]], resulting in a 3&nbsp;x&nbsp;3 "style" box showing large cap, mid cap and small cap stocks, divided among value, blend, and growth stocks:
{| class="wikitable" |+ {{nowrap|Table 1. Total Market Index Style Box (%)}} | ! Value ! Blend ! Growth |- ! Large Cap |align="center" |LV ||align="center" |LB ||align="center" | LG |- ! Mid Cap |align="center" |MV ||align="center" |MB ||align="center" | MG |- ! Small Cap |align="center" |SV ||align="center" |SB ||align="center" | SG |}
You may also see an expanded breakdown of market cap ranges that includes Mega cap, Micro cap, and Nano cap stocks.
{| class="wikitable" |+ Table 2. Market capitalization ! Size Characterization ! Capitalization Range |- | Mega capitalization stocks || Over $200 billion dollars |- | Large capitalization stocks || Between $10 billion dollar and $200 billion dollars |- | Mid capitalization stocks || Between $2 billion and $10 billion dollars |- | Small capitalization stocks || Between $300 million and $2 billion dollars |- | Micro capitalization stocks || Between $30 million and $375 million dollars |- | Nano capitalization stocks || Below $50 million dollars |}
In addition to index provider companies, since 1960 the Center for Research in Security Prices [[CRSP equity indexes|CRSP]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.refinitiv.com/en/financial-data/pricing-and-market-data/equities-market-data/center-for-research-in-security-prices| title=Center for Research in Security Prices | publisher=Refinitiv| accessdate=October 21, 2023}}</ref> has provided the academic community with market return data extending from 1926 to the present. CRSP offers Historical Cap-Based Portfolio data tracking micro, small, mid and large-cap stock. For the cap-based portfolios, CRSP ranks all NYSE companies by market capitalization and then divides them into ten equally populated portfolios. Amex and NASDAQ stocks are then placed into the deciles determined by the NYSE breakpoints, based on their market capitalization. CRSP portfolios 1-2 represent large cap stocks, portfolios 3-5 represent mid-caps, portfolios 6-8 represent small caps, and portfolios 9-10 represent a benchmark of micro-cap stocks.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.crsp.chicagobooth.edu/products/documentation/crsp-cap-based-portfolios| title=Historical CRSP Cap-Based Portfolios| publisher=CRSP}}{{dead link}}</ref>
Starting in 2010, CRSP also provides its own investable capitalization-based indexes, which are now tracked by index funds like Vanguard, and defined in a different way from the historical cap-based portfolios (see [[#Index methodology|Index methodology]] below).
