==Indices and funds==
===Index types=== Usually, an index provider supplies three different index returns for its market segment:<ref>{{forum link| p=749823| title=401k Trgt Ret Fund – Pass. to Active Managed, Fee Increase| date=May 29, 2010}}</ref>
*A ''Price Index'' (Price, PR) which does not include dividends or dividend reinvestment. *A ''Gross Dividend Index'' (Total Return, TR) which includes all dividends reinvested. *A ''Net Dividend Index'' (Net Return, NR) which recognizes that the dividends are subject to tax and not received by the investor. Only the remaining portion of the dividend (net of tax) can be reinvested.
For benchmarking international indices, the Net Return index is most commonly used. The Morningstar Index Returns<ref>{{cite web| url=http://news.morningstar.com/index/indexReturn.html| title=Morningstar Index Returns| publisher=Morningstar}}{{dead link}}</ref> identifies indices by type.{{#tag:ref|Note the MSCI international index designator of "NR", such as ''MSCI EAFE NR USD''. MSCI also supplies indices in local currency (LCL) and US Dollars (USD).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mscibarra.com/products/indices/| title=MSCI Equity Indices Overview}}{{dead link}}</ref>|group="note"}}
=== US total market=== In 1974 by Wilshire Associates established the [[wikipedia:Wilshire 5000|Wilshire 5000 Index]], the first index to measure the entirety of the US public market. In 1984, Russell introduced the [[wikipedia:Russell Indexes|Russell 3000 Index]], measuring 98% of the US Market. S&P created its first broad based index of the US market in 1994 with the S&P Composite 1500 index, comprised of the S&P 500, S&P 400, and S&P 600 indices. The index measures approximately 85% of the market. The first retail index fund based on a total market index became available in 1992.
{| class=wikitable |+ Index inception dates and market coverage ! Index provider ! Inception ! Backdate data ! Market coverage |- |align="center"| Wilshire |align="center"| 1974 |align="center"| 1971 |align="center"| 100% |- |align="center"| Russell |align="center"| 1984 |align="center"| 1984 |align="center"| 98% |- |align="center"| Dow Jones |align="center"| 1991 |align="center"| 1987 |align="center"| 100% |- |align="center"|Morningstar |align="center"|1998 |align="center"| 1998 |align="center"| 97% |- |align="center"| MSCI |align="center"| 2004 |align="center"| 2004 |align="center"| 99.5% |- |align="center"| S&P |align="center"| 2006 |align="center"| 2006 (?) |align="center"| 100% |- |align="center"| CRSP |align="center"| 2001 |align="center"| 2002 |align="center"| 100% (?) |}
After 2000, the number of index providers in the US market expanded, and indexes broadened to encompass the total market. Russell added 1000 micro cap stocks to its Russell 3000 index to create its broadest index, the Russell 3000e (extended), encompassing 99% of the US market. In 2006, S&P created its S&P Completion Index, which in combination with the S&P 500 index produced the S&P Total Market Index. Between 2000 and 2010, MSCI, Dow Jones, and Morningstar also created broad based total market indexes. (See Figure 1. for a chart of index provider market coverage.)
At present, only Russell provides total market style indexes (Russell 3000 Value and Russell 3000 Growth).
Broad total market indexes from all providers means very low stock turnover<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.moneychimp.com/articles/index_funds/turnover.htm| title=Portfolio Turnover| publisher=moneychimp| accessdate=October 21, 2023}}</ref> and very similar results across providers, especially over long holding periods.<ref group="note">The data spreadsheet on this page includes data for the Russell 3000 Growth and Russell 3000 Value Indexes</ref> The differences in return are most often attributed to the breadth of micro cap stocks in a total market index. For example, Morningstar (97%), Russell (98%), and MSCI (99.5%) total market indexes hold lower ranges of micro cap market coverage than does the Wilshire 5000 index (99.9%).
