{{Indexing}} [[Category:Indexing]]

The ''' Bloomberg US Aggregate Bond Index''' (ticker: LBUSTRUU), formerly known as the Lehman Aggregate Bond Index and the Barclays US Aggregate Index, was created in 1986 with backdated history going back to 1976. The index has been maintained by Bloomberg L.P. since August 24th 2016.<ref>{{Cite web| title=Bloomberg Completes Acquisition of Barclays Risk Analytics and Index Solutions Business| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/company/announcements/bloomberg-acquisition-barclays-brais/| publisher=Bloomberg| date=August 24, 2016| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831202728/https://www.bloomberg.com/company/announcements/bloomberg-acquisition-barclays-brais/| archive-date=August 31, 2016}}</ref> The index is a primary benchmark for US bond investors, and is a benchmark index for many US index funds. 

==Overview==
The Index is a composite of four major subindices: US Government Index; US Credit Index; US Mortgage Backed Securities Index (1986); and (beginning in 1992) US Asset Backed Securities Index. The index holds investment quality bonds. The ratings are based on S&P, Moody, and Fitch bond ratings. The index does not include [[High yield bonds|high yield bonds]], [[Municipal bonds |municipal bonds]], [[Treasury Inflation Protected Securities| inflation-indexed bonds]], or [[Developed market bonds |foreign currency bonds]].

The index includes these bond asset classes:<ref>{{cite book| author=Richard Ferri| title=All About Index Funds| page=182| isbn=0-07-148492-2}}</ref>
*Government: [[Treasury bonds |Treasury bills, notes, and bonds]], [[Government agency bonds|Agency bonds]]
*[[Corporate bonds|Credit]]: Industrial, Finance, Utility, Yankee Bonds
*[[Mortgage-backed securities|Mortgage backed]], [[GNMA]], FNMA, FHLMC
*[[Asset-backed securities|Asset backed]], Credit card receivables, Auto Loans, Home equity loans

An asset class's relative weighting within the index changes over time as new asset classes are added to the index, as the number of bonds issued rises and falls, and as market security values fluctuate.

In June 2009, as a result of the 2008 financial crisis, Barclay's announced the creation of the US Aggregate Float Adjusted Index that excludes Treasuries, agencies and MBS held in Federal Reserve accounts.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/barclays-capital-announces-the-creation-of-the-us-aggregate-float-adjusted-index-1214078.htm| title=Barclays press release| date=July 30, 2009}}{{dead link}}</ref>

==Index funds==
The Bloomberg US Aggregate Bond Index was formulated as a market benchmark and contains thousands of illiquid bonds. Index fund managers therefore use sampling strategies when attempting to construct index funds tracking the index. The Vanguard Bond Market ETF is a share class of the Vanguard bond market index fund. 

Selected index funds tracking the Bloomberg US Aggregate Bond Index:
* BNY Mellon Bond Market Index Fund - {{MStarFundLink|DBMIX}}
* iShares Core US Aggregate Bond ETF - {{MStarFundLink|AGG}}
* Infrastructure Capital Bond Income ETF - {{MStarFundLink|BNDS}}
* T. Rowe Price QM U.S. Bond Index Fund - {{MStarFundLink|PBDIX}}
* Nuveen Lifecycle Index Fund - {{MStarFundLink|TRILX}}
* Vanguard Total Bond Market ETF (Float-Adjusted) - {{MStarFundLink|BND}}
* Vanguard Total Bond Market Index Fund (Float-Adjusted) - {{MStarFundLink|VBTLX}}

