The '''{{PAGENAME}}''' is a [[Free-float methodology|free-float]],<ref group="note"> In March 2013, FTSE adopted a fundamental policy of using actual free float percentages (rounded up to the next 1%) in its indexes. The move was taken to reduce unnecessary turnover in the indexes. See [http://www.ftse.com/Indices/FTSE_Index_Standards/Free_Float.jsp Free Float Adjusted - FTSE], for extended discussion. </ref> market-capitalization weighted index representing the performance of around 3031 small cap companies in 46 developed and [[Emerging market stocks|emerging markets]] worldwide, excluding the USA. The index is derived from the FTSE Global Equity Index Series<ref> [http://www.ftse.com/Indices/FTSE_All_World_Index_Series/Downloads/FTSE_GEIS_Brochure_Final_Version.pdf FTSE GEIS Brochure] </ref> and was launched in September 2003 (base date December 31, 2002).<ref>[http://www.ftse.com/vanguard/Home/ftse-other-indexes Other FTSE benchmarks used by Vanguard], FTSE Global Small Cap ex US Index tab, Fact Sheet as of 28-June-13.</ref>
The index is tracked by the Vanguard FTSE All-World ex US Small Cap index fund investor shares (VFSVX) and the Vanguard FTSE All-World ex-US Small-Cap ETF (VSS).<ref group="note"> The FTSE All-World ex-US Small-Cap Index Fund is also available in an Institutional (VFSNX) share class. This share class is commonly used in the corporate retirement plan market. </ref>
==Methodology== The FTSE Global Small Cap ex US Index defines small cap stocks as companies ranked below the top 86%, but within the top 98%, of the index universe by full market capitalization. In order to reduce turnover, the index employs buffer zones around these defined boundaries.<ref> [http://www.ftse.com/vanguard/Content/docs/FTSE_Global_Equity_Index_Series_Index_Rules.pdf?567 Index Ground Rules], pp. 4, 19. </ref>
